T1  - Best Nonparametric Bounds on Demand Responses
AU  - Blundell, Richard
AU  - Browning, Martin
AU  - Crawford, Ian
Y1  - 2008/11/01
PY  - 2008
DA  - 2008/11/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA6069
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 1227
EP  - 1262
VL  - 76
IS  - 6
KW  - Demand responses
KW  - bounds
KW  - revealed preference
KW  - partial identification
KW  - set identification
KW  - inequality restrictions
KW  - relative prices
KW  - semiparametric regression
KW  - changing tastes
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA6069
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This paper uses revealed preference inequalities to provide the tightest possible (best) nonparametric bounds on predicted consumer responses to price changes using consumer-level data over a finite set of relative price changes. These responses are allowed to vary nonparametrically across the income distribution. This is achieved by combining the theory of revealed preference with the semiparametric estimation of consumer expansion paths (Engel curves). We label these expansion path based bounds on demand responses as E-bounds. Deviations from revealed preference restrictions are measured by preference perturbations which are shown to usefully characterize taste change and to provide a stochastic environment within which violations of revealed preference inequalities can be assessed.
ER  - 

